   <titles>
      <title>Orientation of Space</title>
      <plain.title>Orientation</plain.title>
   </titles>
   <intro>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>In this section, we introduce the concept of ‘orientation of space’. It is the key to a geometric interpretation of the determinant, developed in the next section.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>‘Orientation of space’ is as fundamental as the fact that we have two kinds of hands, ‘left’ and ‘right’. Reflection through a mirror turns the image of one hand into an image of the other hand. But there is no known way of physically turning a right hand into a left hand or vice versa.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>Thus we need to find a mathematical way of distinguishing between ‘left hand’ and ‘right hand’ and, more generally, an object from its mirrored sibling. – The concept of orientation of space does exactly that.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </intro>
   <legitimate.children>
      <unit unitid="SubSec_nDimensionalOrientation" standalone="false">
         <titles>
            <title>n-Dimensional Orientation</title>
            <plain.title>n-Dimensional Orientation</plain.title>
         </titles>
         <body>
            <block>
               <block.body>
                  <def type="Definition" id="Def_Orientation">
                     <caption>Orientation</caption>
                     <associate type="Comment">
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Thus <math>
                                    <latex>\omega(\Vect{x}_1,\dots ,\Vect{x}_n)</latex>
                                 </math> is either <math>
                                    <latex>+1</latex>
                                 </math> or <math>
                                    <latex>-1</latex>
                                 </math>. More specifically:</para.body>
                           </para>
                           <ul>
                              <li>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>
                                       <math>
                                          <latex>\omega(\Vect{x}_1,\dots ,\Vect{x}_n) = +1</latex>
                                       </math> if <math>
                                          <latex>\det[\Vect{x}_1,\dots ,\Vect{x}_n]</latex>
                                       </math> is positive.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </li>
                              <li>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>
                                       <math>
                                          <latex>\omega(\Vect{x}_1,\dots ,\Vect{x}_n) = -1</latex>
                                       </math> if <math>
                                          <latex>\det[\Vect{x}_1,\dots ,\Vect{x}_n]</latex>
                                       </math> is negative.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </li>
                           </ul>
                        </info>
                     </associate>
                     <associate type="Example">
                        <showme.pack.ref showmePackID="Exa_Orientation"/>
                        <info>
                           <info.caption>Example</info.caption>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Examples of finding the orientation given by a tuple of vectors.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </associate>
                     <def.body>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>An <math>
                                 <latex>n</latex>
                              </math>-tuple of vectors <math>
                                 <latex>(\Vect{x}_1,\dots ,\Vect{x}_n)</latex>
                              </math> in <math>
                                 <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                              </math> with <math>
                                 <latex>\det[ \Vect{x}_1\ \dots\ \Vect{x}_n]\neq 0</latex>
                              </math> represents the orientation</para.body>
                        </para>
                        <math.array column="3">
                           <row rowspan="1">
                              <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                                 <math>
                                    <latex>\omega(\Vect{x}_1,\dots ,\Vect{x}_n)</latex>
                                 </math>
                              </cell>
                              <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                                 <math>
                                    <latex>:=</latex>
                                 </math>
                              </cell>
                              <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                                 <math>
                                    <latex>\dfrac{\det [ \Vect{x}_1\ \dots\ \Vect{x}_n]}{\abs{ \det [ \Vect{x}_1\ \dots\ \Vect{x}_n] } }</latex>
                                 </math>
                              </cell>
                           </row>
                        </math.array>
                     </def.body>
                  </def>
                  <xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
                              href="OrientationProperties_Prop.xml"/>
               </block.body>
            </block>
         </body>
      </unit>
