      <unit unitid="SubSec_0DimensionalOrientation" standalone="false">
         <titles>
            <title>0-Dimensional Orientation</title>
            <plain.title>0-Dimensional Orientation</plain.title>
         </titles>
         <body>
            <block>
               <block.body>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>In addition, it is useful to distinguish two orientations on a 0-dimensional space; i.e. of a point. An orientation of a point <math>
                           <latex>P</latex>
                        </math> is given by assigning the value <math>
                           <latex>+1</latex>
                        </math> or <math>
                           <latex>-1</latex>
                        </math> to <math>
                           <latex>P</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>This formal definition has no intuitive content. Still, it is useful, for example, in the formulation of the 
				<subordinate>
                           <hot>Fundamental Theorem of Calculus</hot>
                           <companion>
                              <unit.ref unitId="Sub_Orientation0"/>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Details on this use of <math>
                                          <latex>0</latex>
                                       </math>-dimensional orientation</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </companion>
                        </subordinate>
				and its generalization to Stokes' Theorem.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </block.body>
            </block>
         </body>
